1. Recursive DFS : T.C. - O(N), S.C. - O(H), H is the height of tree : BEST - O(LOGN) : Balanced tree, WORST - O(N) : DEGENERATED TREE (SKEWED)

Approach: Depth is the height of the tree, one node means, depth is 1, this approach goes from one node to the end node (DFS)

class Solution:
    def maxDepth(self, root: Optional[TreeNode]) -> int:
        if not root:
            return 0
        return 1 + max(self.maxDepth(root.left),self.maxDepth(root.right))
        
2. Iterative DFS: T.C. - O(N), S.C. - O(N)

Approach: Stack stores two elements in a list within the same box [[root, depth]], depth is stored to 1, 
but result is stored to zero for empty tree. I missed (if node) its for empty tree, or if no children exists.
Syntax can cause problems, [[]], ([])

class Solution:
    def maxDepth(self, root: Optional[TreeNode]) -> int:
        stack = [[root,1]]
        res = 0

        while stack:
            node, depth = stack.pop()

            if node:
                res = max(res,depth)
                stack.append([node.left,depth+1])
                stack.append([node.right,depth+1])
        return res


3. Breadth First Search: T.C. - O(N), S.C. - O(N)

Approach: Here while and for loop both are used because we are traversing level by level so for each level the
loop has to run for only the existing nodes at that level and then update the depth. While is for no of nodes over all
and for loop is from no of nodes in that level

class Solution:
    def maxDepth(self, root: Optional[TreeNode]) -> int:
        q = deque()
        if root:
            q.append(root)
        
        level = 0
        while q:
            for i in range(len(q)):
                node = q.popleft()
                if node.left:
                    q.append(node.left)
                if node.right:
                    q.append(node.right)
            level += 1
        return level
